      "title": "Quick question first\u2026",
      "question": "A current-carrying wire in a magnetic field experiences a force. What happens to this force if the current is doubled?",
      "options": [
        "The force stays the same",
        "The force is halved",
        "The force doubles",
        "The force quadruples"
      ],
      "correctIndex": 2,
      "misconceptionFeedback": "\u26a0\ufe0f Common misconception! From F = BIl, the force is directly proportional to the current I. Doubling I doubles F. The force also depends on the magnetic flux density B and the length of wire in the field l.",
      "correctFeedback": "\u2713 Correct! F = BIl \u2014 force is directly proportional to current. Doubling the current doubles the force on the wire.",
      "bestSource": "BEST resource: AQA Physics specification 4.7.3 \u2014 Motor effect"
    },
    {
      "id": "concept",
      "type": "concept",
      "uiTag": "Concept",
      "uiColor": "blue",
      "title": "The Motor Effect",
      "bodyHTML": "When a current-carrying conductor is placed in a magnetic field, it experiences a <strong>force</strong> \u2014 this is called the <strong>motor effect</strong>. The force is greatest when the current is perpendicular to the magnetic field, and zero when they are parallel. The size of the force is given by <strong>F = BIl</strong>, where B is the magnetic flux density, I is the current, and l is the length of conductor in the field.",
      "keyEquation": "F = B \u00d7 I \u00d7 l",
      "diagram": {
        "type": "equation-breakdown",
        "variables": [
          { "symbol": "F", "label": "Force",                 "unit": "N", "color": "cyan"   },
          { "symbol": "B", "label": "Magnetic flux density", "unit": "T", "color": "purple" },
          { "symbol": "I", "label": "Current",               "unit": "A", "color": "amber"  },
          { "symbol": "l", "label": "Length in field",       "unit": "m", "color": "blue"   }
        ],
        "relationships": [
          "Bigger B \u2192 greater force",
          "Bigger I \u2192 greater force",
          "Longer wire in field \u2192 greater force",
          "Current parallel to field \u2192 no force"
        ]
      },
      "keyWords": ["motor effect", "force", "magnetic flux density", "tesla", "current", "conductor"],
      "commonErrors": [
        "Using the length of the whole wire, not just the length inside the magnetic field",
        "Forgetting the force is zero when current is parallel to the field",
        "Mixing up the units for B (tesla, not amps)"
      ]
    },
